Exercise 16.32: What happens during template argument deduction?

Answer:
The compiler uses types of the arguments in the call to find the template arguments that match best.

Exercise 16.33: Name two type conversions allowed on function arguments
involved in template argument deduction.

Answer:
1)Removal of top level const.
2)Function To Pointer.

Exercise 16.34: Given only the following code, explain whether each of
these calls is legal. If so, what is the type of T? If not, why not?

template <class T> int compare(const T&, const T&);
(a) compare("hi", "world");
(b) compare("bye", "dad");

Answer:
a) Illegal, since "hi" will be converted to char[2] and "world" will be converted to char[5] and since
the size doesn't match and thus the types won't match.
b) Legal, since "bye" will be converted to char[3] and "dad" will also be converted to char[3], their
sizes equal and thus they will match.

Exercise 16.35: Which, if any, of the following calls are errors? If the call is
legal, what is the type of T? If the call is not legal, what is the problem?

template <typename T> T calc(T, int);
template <typename T> T fcn(T, T);
double d; float f; char c;
(a) calc(c, 'c');
(b) calc(d, f);
(c) fcn(c, 'c');
(d) fcn(d, f);

Answer:
a) Legal, T is of type char.
b) Legal, T is of type double.
c) Legal, T is of type char.
d) Illegal, d and f are of different types.

Exercise 16.36: What happens in the following calls:

template <typename T> f1(T, T);
template <typename T1, typename T2) f2(T1, T2);

int i = 0, j = 42, *p1 = &i, *p2 = &j;
const int *cp1 = &i, *cp2 = &j;
(a) f1(p1, p2);
(b) f2(p1, p2);
(c) f1(cp1, cp2);
(d) f2(cp1, cp2);
(e) f1(p1, cp1);
(f) f2(p1, cp1);

Answer:
a) f1 will be generated as f1(int*, int*).
b) f2 will be generated as f2(int*, int*).
c) Top const of cp1 will be removed and f1 will be generated as f1(int*, int*).
d) Top const of cp1 will be removed and f2 will be generated as f2(int*, int*).
e) f1(int*, const int*) will be called however the template specifies both arguments must be of the same type.
f) f2(int*, const int*) will be called and since f2 requires T1 and T2 the call is legal and the following will be
generated f2(int*,int*).

Exercise 16.37: The library max function has two function parameters and
returns the larger of its arguments. This function has one template type
parameter. Could you call max passing it an int and a double? If so, how?
If not, why not?

Answer:
Calling max is not possible since the the two arguments has be to be of the same type.

Exercise 16.38: When we call make_shared (§ 12.1.1, p. 451), we have to
provide an explicit template argument. Explain why that argument is needed
and how it is used.

Answer:
This argument is needed for make_shared to know which object it suppose to allocate memory for.

Exercise 16.39: Use an explicit template argument to make it sensible to
pass two string literals to the original version of compare from § 16.1.1 (p.
652).

Answer:
template <typename T>
int compare(const T &v1, const T &v2)
{
    if (v1 < v2) return -1;
    if (v2 < v1) return 1;
    return 0;
}

Calling compare<std::string>(const char*,const char*) will cause a conversion from const char* to string and thus
the relational operators of string will be used.

Exercise 16.40: Is the following function legal? If not, why not? If it is
legal, what, if any, are the restrictions on the argument type(s) that can be
passed, and what is the return type?

template <typename It>
auto fcn3(It beg, It end) -> decltype(*beg + 0)
{
// process the range
return *beg; // return a copy of an element from the range
}

Answer:
The function is legal, argument types must point to a type that addition with an int can be passed, since decltype will be
called on a rvalue the type returned will be the same as the type returned from the addition operator.

Exercise 16.41: Write a version of sum with a return type that is
guaranteed to be large enough to hold the result of the addition.

Answer:
template<typename T1, typename T2>
auto sum(T1 a, T2 b) -> decltype(a+b)
{
    return a+b;
}

Exercise 16.42: Determine the type of T and of val in each of the
following calls:

template <typename T> void g(T&& val);
int i = 0; const int ci = i;
(a) g(i);
(b) g(ci);
(c) g(i * ci);

Answer:
a) T is of type int& and val is of type int& && which collapses to int&.
b) T is of type const int& and val is of type const int& && which collapses to const int&.
c) T is of type int&& and val is of type int&& && which collapses to int&&.

Exercise 16.43: Using the function defined in the previous exercise, what
would the template parameter of g be if we called g(i = ci)?

Answer:
The assignment will return an lvalue referring to i and the call will be g(i) and T will be int&.

Exercise 16.44: Using the same three calls as in the first exercise,
determine the types for T if g’s function parameter is declared as T (not
T&&). What if g’s function parameter is const T&?

template <typename T> void g(T val);
int i = 0; const int ci = i;
(a) g(i);
(b) g(ci);
(c) g(i * ci);

Answer:
a) If g's function parameter is T then T will be int.
If g's function parameter is const T& then T will be int.
b)If g's function parameter is T then T will be an int.
  If g's function parameter is const T& then T will be int.
c)If g's function parameter is T then T be an int.
  If g's function parameter is const T& then T int.


Exercise 16.45: Given the following template, explain what happens if we
call g on a literal value such as 42. What if we call g on a variable of type
int?

template <typename T> void g(T&& val) { vector<T> v; }

Answer:
Calling g(42) is g(int&&&& val) which will be collapsed to g(int&& val) instantiating T as int and v will be of type vector<int>.
Calling g with lvalue to an rvalue template parameter will cause T to be deduced as int& --> g(int& && val) which will be collapsed to int&
and v will be vector<int&> which is illegal

Exercise 16.46: Explain this loop from StrVec::reallocate in § 13.5 (p.
530):

for (size_t i = 0; i != size(); ++i)
alloc.construct(dest++, std::move(*elem++));

Answer:
We iterate through all the elements and for each element it uses * to get its lvalue
then it uses std::move to get its rvalue reference to force the call to the move constructor.

Exercise 16.49: Explain what happens in each of the following calls:

template <typename T> void f(T);
template <typename T> void f(const T*);
template <typename T> void g(T);
template <typename T> void g(T*);
int i = 42, *p = &i;
const int ci = 0, *p2 = &ci;
g(42); g(p); g(ci); g(p2);
f(42); f(p); f(ci); f(p2);

Answer:
g(42) --> since g(42) matches g(T), g(int) will be instantiated.
g(p) --> p is of type int* --> g(T*) will match --> g(int*) will be instantiated.
g(ci) --> ci is of type const int --> g(T) will match and will be called --> g(const int) will be instantiated.
g(p2) --> p2 is of type const int* --> g(T*) will match and called --> g(const int*) will be instantiated.
f(42) --> 42 is an int rvalue --> f(T) will match and called --> f(int) will be instantiated.
f(p) --> p is of type int* --> f(T) is an exact match while f(const T*) requires a conversion --> f(int*) will be instantiated.
f(ci) --> ci is of type const int --> f(T) is an exact match --> f(const int) will be instantiated.
f(p2) --> p2 is of type const int* --> f(const T*) is an exact match --> f(const int*) will be instantiated.